# numpy

## Introduction

A NumPy matrix-multiply benchmark. It times `np.matmul` on two large
random `n × n` matrices, exercising the multithreaded BLAS backend
(OpenBLAS/MKL) that NumPy links against. It is a quick check of
multi-core dense linear-algebra throughput on a node.

## Installation

Only NumPy is required:

```bash
module load miniforge/23.11.0-0
pip install numpy      # once
```

The benchmark itself is `mat_mult.py` in this directory.

## Usage

### Automated, many runs — `job_*_all_example.sh`

`job_full_all_example.sh` / `job_half_all_example.sh` submit one Slurm
job per node over a list, sweeping the BLAS thread count. Edit the
`nodes`, `partition`, `cpu_count`, and `output_dir` variables at the top,
then run the script to submit.

### Single run — root dir

```bash
module load miniforge/23.11.0-0
time python mat_mult.py        # set n inside the script; time = matmul wall clock
```

Set the BLAS thread count with e.g. `export OMP_NUM_THREADS=8` (or
`OPENBLAS_NUM_THREADS` / `MKL_NUM_THREADS`) before running.

## Analysis

Each run prints `<seconds> seconds to matrix multiply`. Lower is better;
compare across thread counts to see BLAS scaling. For an `n × n` matmul
the work is ≈ `2·n³` FLOPs, so GFLOP/s ≈ `2·n³ / time / 1e9`.
